<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Actually Matters for Container Growing in Cool Climates</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Compact growth habits.</strong> Containers limit root space, so smaller plants are more reliable.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Faster maturity.</strong> Shorter growing windows mean crops need to finish earlier.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Cool-weather performance.</strong> Some varieties handle lower temperatures better than others.
  </p>

  <p>
    When these factors line up, container growing becomes much more predictable.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Container Gardens Fail More Often in Cool Climates</h2>

  <p>
    Containers amplify environmental stress.
  </p>

  <p>
    Common issues include:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>soil warming more slowly than expected</li>
    <li>plants stalling in cooler weather</li>
    <li>crops not reaching maturity before conditions change</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These problems are not always obvious at planting time, but they show up later in the season.
  </p>

  <p>
    That is why choosing varieties that will actually finish — and understanding <a href="/guides/will-my-crop-mature-before-first-frost/">whether they will mature before the first frost</a> — makes such a difference.
  </p>
</section>

